al Entire commands for this skill: `entire dispatch`, `entire search`, and `entire explain`, plus standard `git` and manifest reads.\n    31\t- Default to the last 30 days of activity and no more than 50 total search hits unless the user explicitly asks to widen the scope.\n    32\t- Do not dump raw JSON or raw dispatch output. Summarize the evidence.\n    33\t\n    34\t## Process\n    35\t\n    36\t1. Run preflight checks first:\n    37\t\n    38\t```bash\n    39\tgit rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree\n    40\tentire version\n    41\t```\n    42\t\n    43\t- If this is not a git repo, stop and tell the user: `Run this from inside a git repository.`\n    44\t- If the Entire CLI is unavailable, stop and tell the user: `The Entire CLI is required but not installed. Install it from https://entire.io/docs/cli and try again.`\n    45\t\n    46\t2. Treat both `entire dispatch` and `entire search` as authentication-gated. Before printing the response header, confirm the user is authenticated when those commands are needed. If either command reports authentication is required, stop and tell the user:\n    47\t\n    48\t`entire dispatch` and `entire search` require authentication. Run `entire login` and try again.\n    49\t\n    50\t3. Gather the independent inputs in parallel:\n    51\t\n    52\t- Architecture skeleton:\n    53\t\n    54\t```bash\n    55\tgit ls-files | head -200\n    56\tgit shortlog -sne --since=90d\n    57\t```\n    58\t\n    59\tRead `README.md` plus the most relevant manifest that exists, such as `package.json`, `go.mod`, `pyproject.toml`, or `Cargo.toml`.\n    60\t\n    61\t- Current-branch checkpoint anchors:\n    62\t\n    63\t```bash\n    64\tentire explain --short --no-pager\n    65\t```\n    66\t\n    67\tUse this only to collect local checkpoint IDs, timestamps, and prompts for possible drill-down suggestions. It is not the authoritative repo-wide narrative source.\n    68\t\n    69\t- Recent repo narrative:\n    70\t\n    71\t```bash\n    72\tentire dispatch --since 30d --voice neutral\n    73\t```\n    74\t\n    75\tUse dispatch as the spine of the recent-activity section.\n    76\t\n    77\t4. After dispatch returns, derive up to 5 focused search terms from:\n    78\t\n    79\t- the repo name or README title\n    80\t- the most active top-level directories from recent git churn\n    81\t- one or two domain nouns that recur in the dispatch summary\n    82\t\n    83\tThen run focused searches in parallel, for example:\n    84\t\n    85\t```bash\n    86\tentire search \"auth\" --json --limit 10 --date month\n    87\tentire search \"api\" --json --limit 10 --date month\n    88\tentire search \"billing\" --json --limit 10 --date month\n    89\t```\n    90\t\n    91\t- Prefer explicit focused terms over undocumented empty-query behavior.\n    92\t- Deduplicate hits by checkpoint ID.\n    93\t- Cluster useful results by file path and recurring topic.\n    94\t- Cross-reference those clusters with recent git churn to identify hot files that matter in both checkpoint history and commits.\n    95\t- Treat focused search results as the preferred source for repo-wide checkpoint IDs and checkpoint-author signals.\n    96\t\n    97\t5. Build the overview in this order, even if some sections are thin:\n    98\t\n    99\t```text\n   100\tEntire Code Tour:\n   101\t\n   102\t## What this repo is\n   103\t<2-3 sentence summary from README, manifest, and top-level layout>\n   104\t\n   105\t## Architecture at a glance\n   106\t- <directory>: <purpose>\n   107\t- <directory>: <purpose>\n   108\t\n   109\t## Recent activity (last 30 days)\n   110\t- <summarized narrative point anchored to a checkpoint id or commit sha>\n   111\t\n   112\t## Hot files & key contributors\n   113\t- Hot files: <path> (<n> recent checkpoints, <m> recent commits)\n   114\t- Key contributors: <name> (<n> commits, <m> checkpoints when available)\n   115\t\n   116\t## Want to drill in?\n   117\t- \"Show me checkpoint <id>\"\n   118\t- \"Walk me through <hot-file>\"\n   119\t- \"What's <contributor> been working on?\"\n   120\t```\n   121\t\n   122\t6. Keep the structure consistent:\n   123\t\n   124\t- `What this repo is`: summarize purpose, stack, and the main entry points or domains.\n   125\t- `Architecture at a glance`: cover roughly 5-8 top-level directories or grouped areas.\n   126\t- `Recent activity`: distill dispatch into 3-5 high-signal bullets. Anchor each bullet to a checkpoint ID when available, otherwise a commit SHA.\n   127\t- `Hot files & key contributors`: combine checkpoint/search evidence with git churn and `git shortlog`.\n   128\t- `Want to drill in?`: prefer checkpoint IDs from focused search results. Use `entire explain --short --no-pager` results only to supplement current-branch suggestions when repo-wide search coverage is sparse.\n   129\t\n   130\t## Failure Modes\n   131\t\n   132\t- If both dispatch and focused search are empty for the window, keep the header and produce the architecture and contributor sections anyway. Say clearly that there are no recent Entire checkpoints in the selected window and that the overview is relying on git history where needed.\n   133\t- If every focused search returns zero useful hits, say that clearly and fall back to git-only hot files instead of inventing topics from sparse checkpoint data.\n   134\t- If README or a language manifest is missing, say so briefly and infer what you can from the file layout.\n   135\t\n   136\t## Drill-Down Follow-Ups\n   137\t\n   138\tWhen the user asks for a specific checkpoint, run:\n   139\t\n   140\t```bash\n   141\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --full --no-pager\n   142\t```\n   143\t\n   144\tIf `--full` fails, fall back to:\n   145\t\n   146\t```bash\n   147\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --no-pager\n   148\t```\n   149\t\n   150\tWhen the user asks about a hot file or contributor, use the checkpoint IDs or commits already surfaced in the overview as the starting points for the follow-up rather than redoing the whole overview from scratch.\n"}}
